Found the solution: use a parameter called `$event`, like this:

``` html
<div data-ui-event="{ scroll: 'scrollHandler($event)' }">
  lots of lines
  that can be scrolled
  when viewed
  ...
</div>
```

And in the controller, the parameter supplied is a `jQuery` event:

``` javascript
$scope.scrollHandler = function (evt) {
    console.log('evt.target:', evt.target);
};
```

But beware: when `$scope.scrollHandler` is called, it is in a child scope.

So if you want to reference a variable that is in the main controller, you will have to put it on the controller's `$scope` variable, and within `$scope.scrollHandler`, refer to it via `$scope.$parent`. 

Something like this within the controller code, in conjunction with view HTML as above:

``` javascript
$scope.someBooleanVar = false;

$scope.scrollHandler = function (evt) {
    if (someCondition(evt.target)) {
        $scope.$parent.someBooleanVar = true;    // <-- refer to parent scope here
    }
};

```

